TY  - JOUR
AU  - Genesove, David
AU  - Mayer, Christopher
T1  - Loss Aversion and Seller Behavior: Evidence from the Housing Market*
PY  - 2001
Y1  - 2001/11/01
DO  - 10.1162/003355301753265561
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 116
IS  - 4
SP  - 1233
EP  - 1260
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - Data from downtown Boston in the 1990s show that loss aversion determines seller behavior in the housing market. Condominium owners subject to nominal losses 1) set higher asking prices of 25–35 percent of the difference between the property's expected selling price and their original purchase price; 2) attain higher selling prices of 3–18 percent of that difference; and 3) exhibit a much lower sale hazard than other sellers. The list price results are twice as large for owneroccupants as investors, but hold for both. These findings suggest that sellers are averse to realizing (nominal) losses and help explain the positive price-volume correlation in real estate markets.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1162/003355301753265561
ER  - 



